record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1786,
  "cap": "DOS",
  "endpoint": "POST /api/v1/findings/:id/replay",
  "rationale": "The replay SSE handler spawns `bash <repro.sh>` with `kill_on_drop(true)` but no wall-clock timeout, no CPU cap, no memory cap, and no per-tenant concurrency limit. The handler holds the SSE stream open until both stdout and stderr drain AND `child.wait().await` returns, so a repro script that never terminates (`while :; do :; done`, `sleep infinity`, `cat /dev/urandom | gzip > /dev/null`) parks one tokio task plus one bash process per request, indefinitely. `kill_on_drop` only fires if the *client* disconnects and the SSE response future is dropped; a client that holds the connection open keeps the child alive forever. Combined with the integrity gap above (or just a legit but pathological repro.sh from any AI-emitted finding), an authenticated caller can pin all available file descriptors / process slots by firing N parallel replays. The handler also has no separate sandbox lane — the child inherits the daemon's full ambient privileges and network reach, so a runaway loop competes directly with scan/AI work on the daemon host. Static pass missed because spawning a child process with piped stdio is the canonical shape — the gap is the missing timeout wrapper around `child.wait().await`, not a tainted sink.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "build a bundle whose repro.sh is `#!/bin/sh\\nwhile :; do :; done`; fire `for i in $(seq 1 200); do curl -N -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8088/api/v1/findings/<id>/replay?token=<t> & done`; watch daemon CPU + process table fill up while subsequent legitimate requests stall."
}

