{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-core/src/report/run_card.rs",
  "line": 346,
  "cap": "XSS",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/runs/:id/summary.md",
  "rationale": "render_markdown interpolates `card.run_id`, `card.status`, `card.triggered_by`, every `BySplit.key`, and every `PhaseDuration.phase` directly into the markdown body with no escaping, while the HTML sibling (render_html, line 259) carefully runs the same fields through escape_html. The HTML route is safe; the markdown route is the surface that bites. `by_cap.key` comes from `findings.cap`, `by_origin.key` from `findings.finding_origin`, and `by_lang.key` from `payloads.lang` — every one of those is a string the AI Exploration / NovelFinding writers control (see candidate_findings → findings promotion path). The frontend at frontend/src/pages/Findings/FindingDetail.tsx and the new client.ts (lines 100-120ish) consume the summary endpoints; any code path that pipes the .md body through a markdown-to-HTML renderer with HTML enabled (the default for `marked`, `markdown-it`, `react-markdown` with `rehype-raw`) lands `<img src=x onerror=...>` straight into the operator's DOM. Same payload via the .json endpoint then back through a markdown renderer hits the same sink. Static pass missed because the source field never crosses a `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` call inside the Rust crate — the XSS is a contract violation between the safe HTML renderer and the unsafe MD renderer; both export from the same module so a caller naturally assumes parity.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "promote a candidate finding with `cap = \"<img src=x onerror=alert(document.domain)>\"`; GET /api/v1/runs/<run>/summary.md; observe the unescaped tag inside the `## Capability` bullet list; any UI that markdown-renders the body executes the payload."
}
